body:
I tried this code:

```rust
fn my_function(i: usize) -> f32 {
    i as f32 * 42.0
}

fn main() {
    let (mut min, mut max) = (f32::MAX, f32::MIN);
    let data: Vec<f32> = (0..5)
        .map(|i| {
            let val = my_function(i);
            if val > max {
                max = val;
            }
            if val < min {
                min = val;
            }
            val
        })
        .collect();

    for val in data.into_iter() {
        println!("{}", (val - min) / (max - min));
    }
}
```

I expected to see this happen: clippy should say to remove the `.into_iter()`.

Instead, clippy said this:

```
warning: avoid using `collect()` when not needed
  --> src/main.rs:16:8
   |
16 |     }).collect();
   |        ^^^^^^^
17 | 
18 |     for val in data.into_iter() {
   |                ---------------- the iterator could be used here instead
   |
   = note: `#[warn(clippy::needless_collect)]` on by default
   = help: for further information visit https://rust-lang.github.io/rust-clippy/master/index.html#needless_collect
help: use the original Iterator instead of collecting it and then producing a new one
   |
7  ~     
8  | 
9  ~     for val in (0..5).map(|i| {
10 +         let val = my_function(i);
11 +         if val > max {
12 +             max = val;
```

The fix does not work (because iterating two times is needed to have the right value of `(min, max)`), and does not even compile (I tried `--fix`).

### Meta

`rustc --version --verbose`:
```
rustc 1.56.0-nightly (5a19ffe1c 2021-08-13)
binary: rustc
commit-hash: 5a19ffe1c2b99d9e09706cc286aad1ec0868eddb
commit-date: 2021-08-13
host: x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu
release: 1.56.0-nightly
LLVM version: 12.0.1
```

The same problem happens with stable.
